{{Infobox river | name = Pouce Coupe River | image = Pouce Coupe River.JPG | image_size = | image_caption = Pouce Coupe River canyon after the confluence with Saskatoon Creek | source1_location = [[Saddle Hills County]], [[Alberta]] | mouth_location = [[Peace River (Canada)|Peace River]] | mouth_coordinates = {{coord|56.13158|-119.91116|region:CA-AB|name=Peace River|display=inline,title}} | subdivision_type1 = Country | subdivision_name1 = [[Canada]] | length = | source1_elevation = {{convert|860|m|ft|abbr=on}} | mouth_elevation = {{convert|380|m|ft|abbr=on}} | discharge1_avg = | basin_size = }} The '''Pouce Coupe River ''' is a major tributary of the [[Peace River (Canada)|Peace River]] in [[Alberta]] and [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. Its name is officially spelled ''Pouce Coupé River'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Pouce Coupé River|url=http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/search-place-names/unique.php?id=IABZN|work=Querying Canadian Geographical Names|publisher=Natural Resources Canada|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> but it is commonly written without the acute accent.
Originating in Alberta's [[Saddle Hills County]], it flows into British Columbia's [[Peace River Regional District, British Columbia|Peace River Regional District]], then returns in Alberta in [[Clear Hills County]], where it empties into the Peace River.
The region of Pouce Coupe Prairie, from which the river and village of [[Pouce Coupe, British Columbia|Pouce Coupe]] take their names, was called that for a [[Dunneza|Beaver Indian]] Chief named 'Pouscapee'. The first European settler in the region was Hector Tremblay, who built a cabin there in 1898. Tremblay, of [[French people|French]] origin, translated 'Pouskapee's Prairie' into the nearest French words of similar sound ({{lang|fr|pouce coupé}}, meaning "cut thumb" or "cut-off thumb").
==Course== The Pouce Coupe originates in a small lake in [[northern Alberta]], at an elevation of {{convert|860|m|ft}}, in the ''Pouce Coupe Prairie'' of the southern [[Peace River Country]], west of [[Spirit River, Alberta|Spirit River]] and [[Woking, Alberta|Woking]], between Saddle Hills and Blueberry Hill. It flows west and receives the waters of Boone Creek before reaching the British Columbia–Alberta border.
The river then turns northwest to the village of [[Pouce Coupe, British Columbia|Pouce Coupe]]. The Pouce Coupe Regional Park is established on the banks of the river east of the village and [[British Columbia Highway 2|Highway2]], at the confluence with Bissette Creek.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbctourism.com/communities/Pouce_Coupe|title=Pouce Coupe|author=Northern BC Tourism|accessdate=2008-02-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20050111182052/http://www.nbctourism.com/communities/Pouce_Coupe|archivedate=2005-01-11}}</ref>
It receives the waters of Dawson Creek east of the city of [[Dawson Creek, British Columbia|Dawson Creek]], then turns northeast, entering once again the province of Alberta, north of [[Alberta Highway 49|Highway 49]]. The course runs through a canyon that reaches depths of {{convert|220|m|ft}} in this section. [[Ammonite]] fossils harvested from the geological formations opened in the canyon can be found in the Dawson Creek Northern Alberta Railways Park museum. The river continues north and empties into the [[Peace River (Canada)|Peace River]], south of [[Alberta Highway 64|Highway 64]], at an elevation of {{convert|380|m|ft}}.
==Tributaries and crossings== [[Image:Pouce Coupe -Landry bridge.JPG|thumb|right|280px|Landry road bridge]] From its origin to its mouth, Pouce Coupe River encounters the following [[tributary|tributaries]] and crossings: {|class="wikitable" !Tributary/crossings !Location !Remarks |- |Unnamed Lake||<small>{{coord|55.67064|-119.34843|name=Pouce Coupe origin|type:river_region:CA-AB}}</small>||Origin |- |Forestry Road||<small>{{coord|55.67594|-119.68626|name=Forestry Road}}</small>||Bridge |- |Boone Creek||<small>{{Coord|55.66680|-119.88655|region:CA|name=Boone Creek}}</small>||From South, left tributary |- |Tupper River||<small>{{Coord|55.66897|-120.03426|region:CA|name=Tupper River}}</small>||From South, left tributary |- |[[British Columbia]] border||<small>{{Coord|55.66334|-120.00092|region:CA|name=British Columbia border|}}</small>|| |- |Bissette Creek||<small>{{Coord|55.71124|-120.12232|region:CA|name=Bissette Creek}}</small>||From West, left tributary |- |[[Pouce Coupe, British Columbia|Pouce Coupe]] Regional Park||<small>{{Coord|55.71168|-120.12303|region:CA|name=Pouce Coupe Regional Park}}</small>||Camping |- |Briar Ridge Road||<small>{{Coord|55.71318|-120.12156|region:CA|name=Briar Ridge Road}}</small>||Bridge |- |Dawson Creek||<small>{{Coord|55.74090|-120.11801|region:CA|name=Dawson Creek}}</small>||From West, left tributary |- |[[British Columbia Highway 49|Highway 49]]||<small>{{Coord|55.75138|-120.10638|region:CA|name=Dawson Creek}}</small>||Bridge |- |Henderson Creek||<small>{{Coord|55.84762|-120.01283|region:CA|name=Henderson Creek}}</small>||From East, right tributary |- |Landry Road||<small>{{Coord|55.86501|-120.03057|region:CA|name=Landry Road}}</small>||Bridge |- |Saskatoon Creek||<small>{{Coord|55.86964|-120.03057|region:CA|name=Saskatoon Creek|format=dec}}</small>||From West, left tributary |- |[[Alberta]] border||<small>{{Coord|55.88106|-120.00027|region:CA|name=Alberta border|}}</small>|| |- |Doe Creek||<small>{{Coord|55.99577|-119.89380|region:CA|name=Doe Creek}}</small>||From West, left tributary |- |Broche Creek||<small>{{Coord|55.99808|-119.88461|region:CA|name=Broche Creek}}</small>||From East, right tributary |- |[[Peace River (Canada)|Peace River]] ||<small>{{coord|56.13158|-119.91116|name=Pouce Coupe mouth|type:river_region:CA-AB}}</small>||Mouth |- |} {{GeoGroupTemplate}}
